						<tr>
							<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Chapter Four
<br />

<br />
“Where am I?” the gnome thought hazily.  He strained to focus his eyes in the gray light, but it was difficult.  His glasses!  Where were his glasses?  No wonder things looked blurry.  And his head, the top of his head stung, as if it had been scraped raw.  His scalp began to throb in uncomfortable pain.  Thinking about the pain, he realized there was something on his head.  It felt like some kind of cloth… a strange hat, perhaps?  Or a bandage?  He tried to move but found that he could not.  He was being held in place by cords about his hands and feet.  He was trapped in this large wooden chair.
<br />

<br />
“Ah, so his mighty little lordship is awake, is he?”  A new voice, one he had not heard before, different.  “I see my brother has been very kind to you.  You’re lucky to be alive in one piece… well, mostly one piece!” the Iksar laughed.  “Well now, don’t go away… I’ll be back in a moment.”  
<br />

<br />
CJ saw the outline of a large Iksar as the light from the next room entered through the opening door.  Then it was darker again.  His mind began racing.  “Where am I?  What has become of me?” he pondered, striving to keep from panicking.  And then a terrible sinking sensation, almost a nausea swept over him as he realized what the Iksar had said:  “mostly one piece”.  He shuddered and started taking an inventory.  He felt for his fingers, wiggling each, and then his toes, and then his ears.  And then his head hurt again.  “Oh what have they done to me?”
<br />

<br />
A large wooden door opened, torches entered borne by two hooded figures.  Soon a fire was burning in a large fireplace, casting dancing shadows of firelight on the stone walls and across the wooden floor.  The torchbearers retreated from the room.  He was alone again.
<br />

<br />
After a while, (Was it an hour or two or three?  The gnome couldn’t tell…) the door opened again.  This time he could not tell who or what or how many entered.  He was sure that more than two or three had come into the room, but it was difficult to see in the shadows of the dying fire.
<br />

<br />
“Little One.”  His heart sank.  This was not the voice he wanted to hear.  “Welcome to a darkness.  Your days of deceit are ending.  Your days of service just beginning.”  It was the green-eyed dark elf, speaking softly into his left ear from behind.
<br />

<br />
“I… I don’t under… st… stand,” the small nervous craftsman ventured.
<br />

<br />
“Silence!” came the evil command of a woman’s voice.  CJ would have jumped, but couldn’t move.  So only his increasingly rapid beating heart did.  “You will not speak unless spoken to… do you understand, gnome?”  She spat out the words as if they tasted as vile as poison.
<br />

<br />
“Yes, of course,” he whimpered.  He raised his head trying to see who spoke.
<br />

<br />
“Yes, what!?” the female voice demanded.
<br />

<br />
“Yes, your… your…” he faltered, not knowing who he was addressing or what place this was.
<br />

<br />
Suddenly lightning flashed through his mind as his head jerked to the side.  He had been struck hard.  Hard enough to start bleeding on his cheek just below his left eye.
<br />

<br />
“You insolent speck of dust,” hissed another.  “How dare you mock our Lady.”
<br />

<br />
It was all the gnome could do to remain conscious.  “I’m sorry, sir,” was all he could manage.  He tried hard to focus on the shadows circling him, but it was too dim in this darkened chamber. 
<br />

<br />
Soon the shadows stopped dancing (or did they?) and he began to wonder what would happen next.  He wouldn’t have to wonder for long.
<br />

<br />
 
<br />
Chapter Five
<br />

<br />
CJ the artisan awoke suddenly, confused and wondering where he was.  There was some light – a dim light coming in through a window… his window!  Could it be?  He squinted his eyes as best he could and scanned his surroundings.  It appeared to be early dawn and he was back in his own room!  All those terrible things, the dark room, the mysterious shadow figures, the chair… it must have been a nightmare!  That’s it.  It was just a silly nightmare!
<br />

<br />
“Well!” he thought as be began to sit up in his bed… HIS bed!  “I’m not going to be intimidated by any more shadowy patrons in my shop,” he began muttering to himself.  “From now on I’ll just… aaaaarrrgghhhh!”
<br />

<br />
The pain was unbearable.  Like jagged fangs piercing flesh, the pain attacked his feet.  Stabbing, then throbbing, then stabbing again.  He felt a little light-headed as he tried to adjust.  He started to remove his blanket and swing his feet around to get out of bed.   “Aaaaaarrrrgggghhhhh!”
<br />

<br />
The wave of suffering that crashed against his mind nearly crushed him.  It was all he could do to focus his fading gaze on his feet – the source of the greatest pain.
<br />

<br />
“Nooooooooo!” he cried out in near hysteria.  Where were his little toes!?  All he saw was a bloody patch of torn skin on each foot where his little toes should have been.  As he realized what he was looking at, nausea washed over him.  He was drowning, fighting to keep his consciousness.  Exerting all of his will to stay awake, he tried to steady himself.  He didn’t dare move for fear of causing more pain.
<br />

<br />
Instinctively, he raised his hand to his head to run his fingers through his graying wavy hair.  But instead of hair, he encountered cloth.  “Oh no, no... it can’t be,” he thought, thinking that this was becoming the worst nightmare of his life.
<br />

<br />
“Little One.”  That horrible, hated voice!  The gnome jerked his head around to face the source of the sound, but there was no one there!  As he did, pain shot up his legs again, causing him to cringe.  And his head… the top of his head stung as if it had been scraped… or cut!  “No!  No!  This can not be happening,” he cried.  He reached up and grasped the cloth on his head.
<br />

<br />
The cloth on his head slipped away easily, as if an old bandage.  He carefully brought the rag in his hand around in front of his perspiring pale face.  There were traces of blood.  This cloth was indeed a bandage, of sorts.  But it was not made of the gauzy linen usually used for binding wounds.  This cloth was heavier, like canvas and was a completely foul lightless black.  And it smelled of dried blood.  Another wave of nausea washed over him.
<br />

<br />
Fearing what he might find, he dropped the cloth and raised his hand up to the crown of his head.  Moving carefully, as if he might encounter an intricate trap or a deadly sharp blade, he let his finger close in on his skull.
<br />

<br />
The master craftsman found no trap, no blade, and no hair.  As his fingertips touched the raw remnants of his skin, sending tinges of pain around his head, he realized to his total horror that he had no scalp.
<br />

<br />
It was all the poor little man could accept.  CJ Tinkerman passed out, draped across his bed like a worn out puppet.
<br />
 
<br />
Chapter Six
<br />

<br />
When he awoke again, the fading gray light in his room caused him to realize that it must be evening.  The throbbing dull pain coming from his feet and head told him that this was no nightmare.  “Oh, what has happened to me?”
<br />

<br />
“Little One.”  This time the voice was not whispered, but spoke quietly and firmly.  The sound came from his right.
<br />

<br />
CJ looked up at the stranger standing nearby, anger rising within him.  He sat up on the bed.  His rage would know no bounds, he would destroy all who did this to him.  He would kill…  
<br />

<br />
“I don’t think I like that look,” commented a casual feminine voice.   He looked to his left, and saw a hooded figure.  Dressed in an exquisite midnight blue robe, trimmed in gold embroidery, she pushed back her hood.  The gnome gasped as he looked up into her face.  It was the half elf Lady.  The one he had dreamed… no, no… the one he had seen in the darkened room.  His anger melted into fear.
<br />

<br />
“Well, we could always remove more items from this fellow,” offered the green-eyed dark elf in a menacing voice.  “I’m sure there are others who would like a souvenir.”
<br />

<br />
As he realized what was being said, not knowing what else to do, CJ Tinkerman the Gnome, master craftsman, begged for his life.
<br />

<br />
“Please, do not harm me.  I have been damaged enough,” he pleaded.  “Please.  I will do whatever you want, just don’t hurt me anymore.”
<br />

<br />
“Ah there.  You see,” said the Lady in midnight blue to her green-eyed colleague.  “He can be reasonable.  In fact, I think we should help this poor little man.”  She smiled a wickedly delicious grin, her eyes flashing with the sheer delight of what she was doing.
<br />

<br />
“What will you have me do, M’Lady?” the gnome asked humbly, bowing his aching head gingerly.  He knew he had lost.  He surrendered.
<br />

<br />
“And he’s learned some manners, too,” she pointed out, gesturing towards her victim as if the dark elf across the room cared.
<br />

<br />
She leaned in closer to the gnome and hissed venomously, “Listen to me, foolish knave.  You are now our servant and slave.  You will give us one half of all of your profits from this day forth.”  CJ’s mouth dropped open in shock.  How?
<br />

<br />
“Do not even think it!” she spat at him while landing a painfully glancing blow with the hilt of her dagger on his tattered skull.  “Cross us again and we will remove more bits of you.  Every time you disobey or think to deceive or cheat us, we will take another souvenir from your miserable little bag of bones!”
<br />

<br />
The gnome’s blanched expression showed that he fully understood.  This was no idle threat.  His life would be spared, but it would never be the same again.
<br />

<br />
“And another thing, Little One,” she glanced at her guildmate as she used of his favorite name for the gnome.  “You will use your artistic skills to craft whatsoever the officers and patrons of the Shadowfire Guild require.  Your payment for such services will be to keep your life.” 
<br />

<br />
With that she turned to leave the room.  Nodding, CJ watched silently as her dark elf companion backed towards the door, following her.
<br />

<br />
Just as she was about to leave, she turned, “Serve the Shadowfire well and live.  Cross the Shadowfire and burn in darkness.  It is your choice.”  She smiled and stepped through the darkened doorway.
<br />

<br />
“Little One,” the green-eyed dark elf smiled as he closed the door behind him.
<br />

<br />
Little One was alone.  His room was dark – darker that it had ever been before.
<br />

<br />
 
<br />
THE END?
<br />

<br />

